<subSubSection pageNumber="703" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="703">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">Note:</emphasis>
Britten (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">J. Bot.</emphasis>
47, Suppl. 1909; 50: 312-314. 1912) argued that this apparent novelty results from a typographic error for the previously published 
<taxonomicName authority="L. (1753)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Ophrys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="insectifera" variety="arachnites">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">O. insectifera</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">arachnites</emphasis>
L. (1753)
</taxonomicName>
. Stearn (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">
Introd. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rayâ€™s">Ray's</normalizedToken>
Syn. Meth. Stirp. Brit.
</emphasis>
(Ray Soc. ed.): 42-68. 1973) evidently agreed as he did not list the name as new. However, Rothmaler (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">Repert. Spec. Nov. Regni Veg.</emphasis>
49: 280. 1941) did accept 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1754" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Ophrys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arachnites">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">O. arachnites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a new combination. He has been followed by Greuter (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">Candollea</emphasis>
44: 566. 1989) who, however, treated the name as a 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="703">nomen dubium et confusum.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
